Succession Royal succession is governed by the Succession Act.
The Succession Act is a federal law that governs who is a successor under the law of succession. It deals with the distribution of the assets of a deceased person.
The Act divides the assets of a deceased person into a ‘personal estate’ and a ‘real estate’. The ‘personal estate’ consists of all the property that belonged to the deceased person and their property rights at the time of death.

tiiuae-falcon-7b:
Vartashen was mainly a Udi clan territory.
It was a strategic part of the Kartsahak region, situated between the Kartsahak River, the Arpa River and the Kavatakan River. It included the villages of Arda, Hovs, Kalach, Karahak, Karhul, Kavatakan, Kher and Zartrask.
It was situated north of the Kartsahak river, east of the Arpa river and south of the Kavatakan river. The river was named after a mountain (Kartsahak) and the river (Kavatakan), while the "H" in Vartashen may have derived from the "H" sound of Arpa (the river), as the mountains are named Hovs and Hovshen.

original_sentence: Voroshil Gukasyan, Soviet linguist, Caucasologist and specialist in the Udi language and Caucasian Albanian inscriptions.
tiiuae-falcon-7b:
Voroshil Gukasyan, Soviet linguist, Caucasologist, and Armenianist, was born in Yerevan in 1925, in the family of a famous literary critic, poet and historian. His father, Ara Gukasyan (1892-1955) was an important representative of the Armenian Enlightenment and a member of the Soviet Academy of Sciences. Voroshil Gukasyan was graduated from the Moscow State University (1944) and the Moscow State University of Linguistics and the Humanities (1955).
In 1955, Voroshil Gukasyan started his scientific career at the Department of Linguistics, Soviet Academy of Sciences. At the age of 27, a year after his graduation, he was appointed as an assistant professor, and then as an associate professor. In 1962, he became a full professor. He was the head of the department of “Slavic Studies” at the Institute of Linguistics of the Academy of Sciences of the USSR for many years. He was also a professor of the Slavic Department at the Faculty of Philology of the Moscow State University. He has been the president of the Scientific Council of the Slavic Department of the Moscow State University.

original_sentence: World War I brought a change in the tastes of the theatregoing public.
tiiuae-falcon-7b:
World War I brought a new awareness of the need for medical supplies.
In December 1914, the Ladies' Relief Corps was formed, and the first official meeting was held in the Union Building, Wollongong.
The members were keen to help, and immediately began knitting.
Many of the early members were involved at the Wollongong Red Cross Hospital.
They knitted scarves to be sent overseas to the soldiers, and also knitted socks and mufflers for the wounded at home.
The first shipment of 70 scarves left Wollongong in 1915, but the numbers soared to over 30,000 by the end of the war.
The first shipment left Wollongong on 30th October, 1915, and arrived in England on 26th November, 1915.
By the end of the war, Wollongong's Ladies Relief Corps had knitted 30,500 scarves and 20,000 mufflers.
The last shipment left Wollongong on 30th April, 1919.
The Australian War Memorial has a collection of some of the scarves knitted and donated by the Ladies' Relief Corps.
